            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Karen Lin Miller\u2019s story is woven into the fog and ambition of San Francisco. Born in the Richmond District to Taiwanese immigrants who ran a small grocery store, she straddled two worlds. Her name, Karen, was a deliberate choice by her parents for assimilation, a stark contrast to the Mandarin spoken at home. Watching her father navigate the city\u2019s complex permitting process for his business planted the seed for her future. She saw government not as an adversary, but as a puzzle to be solved for the benefit of all.\n\nShe attended San Francisco State University, earning a degree in Public Policy, driven by a desire to improve the systems that shaped her community. Her career began in the mid-90s at a city agency, a world of paper files and bureaucratic inertia. A key turning point came with the first dot-com boom. While many peers left for lucrative tech startups, Karen saw the potential for technology within public service. She dedicated herself to bridging the gap, becoming the go-to person for translating old processes into digital solutions.\n\nHer personal life is as rooted in the city as her professional one. She met her husband, David Miller, an architect, at a contentious neighborhood planning meeting; they bonded over a shared vision for a more livable city. They raised their son, Leo, now away at college, in their modest Noe Valley home.\n\nKaren\u2019s daily routine is a testament to her belief in public infrastructure. She takes the J-Church MUNI line downtown, reading reports on her tablet. Her work involves wrangling code, budgets, and inter-departmental politics to launch services like online permit applications\u2014the very thing that once frustrated her father. Weekends are for the Noe Valley Farmers' Market, long walks with David through Glen Canyon Park, and dim sum with her aging mother.\n\nHer hope is not for wealth or fame, but for legacy. She dreams of retiring knowing the digital tools she helped build have made San Francisco a more efficient and equitable place. She is a pragmatic steward of the city she loves, often frustrated by its imperfections but unwavering in her commitment to improving it from within."
